  "slug": "peach-pie",
  "title": "Peach pie",
  "subtitle": "Double-crust summer pie with spiced peach filling",
  "excerpt": "A classic double-crust American peach pie with a buttery shortcrust pastry and a lightly spiced filling of fresh peaches thickened with cornflour. The fruit slumps during baking and the juices bubble through the vents.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Peach pie is one of the canonical American summer pies, associated with Southern states where white and yellow peaches are grown commercially. It appears in virtually every American general cookbook from the nineteenth century onward. This version follows the double-crust method documented in Joy of Cooking (Rombauer, Becker and Becker, 2006) and the pastry ratio used by Dorie Greenspan in Baking from My Home to Yours (2006).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Peaches release a lot of juice during baking. The cornflour thickens those juices into a glossy gel that holds the filling together when sliced. Too little cornflour and the filling is watery; too much and it becomes gluey. The amount here is calibrated for ripe, fresh fruit. Overripe peaches release more liquid: add an extra teaspoon of cornflour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "type": "tip"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "text": "Use ripe peaches that smell sweet. Underripe peaches bake into a mealy, acidic filling. If all you can find are hard peaches, leave them at room temperature for 1 to 2 days before making the pie. The pie is not a recipe for rescuing poor fruit.",
                "type": "text"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
